description.plain:
This Louisiana indie-rock band, formed in 1989 by singer, songwriter and guitarist Jeff Mangum, is the furthest thing from a typical band. For one, Mangum played most of the instruments himself. His credits on the debut LP (On Avery Island) include bells, xylophone and air organ. This instrument list suggests the band’s eclectic sound. Defining their genre difficult, as they combine folk, punk, psychedelic rock, blues, indie-rock and and a little carnival music to create a unique, instantly recognizable body of work.

The group’s most famous work is their second LP, In the Aeroplane Over the Sea (1998). The searing concept album was met with mixed reviews upon release, but over time has become a classic of indie music. It has been picked by many publications as one of the best albums of the nineties, and is an influence to many bands, including Arcade Fire, Bright Eyes, and AJJ.

description.plain:
“A Baby For Pree”, sometimes mistitled as “A Baby For Free”, is the 4th track from Neutral Milk Hotel’s debut album, On Avery Island.

This song was written for Jeff Mangum’s friend, called Pree, when she gave birth to her first child, and as such centers around a theme of pregnancy throughout.

The melody for this track is reused for “Where You’ll Find Me Now”, making this an intro of sorts to it.

This is also the last song that was written for the album.

songs.full_title: April 8th by Neutral Milk Hotel
songs.title: April 8th

description.plain:
This track is about reclusive artist Henry Darger, whose 15,000 page novel, The Story of the Vivian Girls, in What is Known as the Realms of the Unreal, of the Glandeco-Angelinian War Storm, Caused by the Child Slave Rebellion, and 300 associated paintings were not discovered or known of until after his death. Darger, in a similar way to Jeff Mangum, is considered a genius who hid much of his art from the world.

Much of Darger’s work was inspired by the story of Elsie Paroubek, a girl who was kidnapped and murdered on April 8, 1911, which was likely the inspiration for the title of the song.

songs.full_title: Gardenhead / Leave Me Alone by Neutral Milk Hotel
songs.title: Gardenhead / Leave Me Alone

description.plain: In this song, the narrator is experiencing a revelation about his relationship with both drugs and a girl that isn’t good for him. The girl and the drugs are most often written about with a sense of duality and partnership, leading the listener to believe that the girl is keeping the narrator on drugs and that the narrator intends to leave this girl and go off the drugs immediately. In the last verse, Mangum finally makes the line fine between the girl and the drugs, pleading the girl to save herself and come with him. Mangum brings out the feeling of frustration that one experiences when they feel like they have found a higher meaning that no one else seems to understand, without being overly aggressive. Overall, this song is about finding the bad things in ones life and finding the strength to leave what is hurting you, but also feeling the pull of trying to save people who are dragging themselves and you down along the way.

description.plain:
This song is about Jeff’s experience with a ghost supposedly living in his home, that, like many songs on this album, ended up becoming a reference to Anne Frank.



As with several other songs on In the Aeroplane over the Sea, “Ghost” blends seamlessly into the following track, “[untitled]”. The song begins as a simple unaccompanied acoustic track, but several horns, extremely distorted electric guitars, and drums join Mangum as the song continues, reaching a crescendo as an eerie synth – likely representing the ghost themself – delivers the outro melody in Mangum’s place.

songs.full_title: Holland, 1945 by Neutral Milk Hotel
songs.title: Holland, 1945

description.plain:
Jeff Mangum has stated in concerts multiple times that this song was mainly inspired by the diary of Anne Frank, as with most of the subjects explored on the album, which also links again back to the title. Using the kaleidoscopic lyricism found spread across In the Aeroplane Over The Sea, he explores his love and admiration of Anne Frank, and travels through different visions of how her legacy lives on.

This song was the last to be named on the album, and was originally called “Untitled”, just like the tenth track on the album. Eventually Jeff Mangum settled on two titles given by Chris Bilheimer, who was in charge of art direction, when he was working on a broadsheet-style lyric sheet for the album, and “Holland” and “1945” were placed together. Jeff Mangum liked the two titles so much he didn’t know which one to choose, so Bilheimer suggested that he use both.

songs.title: I Love How You Love Me
songs.title_with_featured: I Love How You Love Me

description.plain:
Following the breakup of Neutral Milk Hotel, the singer Jeff Magnum attended a live event in Auckland, New Zealand. The group of individuals that performed at the event including, Magnum, Laura Carter, and Chris Knox, were described as the World of Wild Beards Incorporated.



In Magnum’s explanation for band name he described a business from the early 1900’s titled Walking Wall of Beards Incorporated. This most likely influenced the title of the Neutral Milk Hotel website, (http://www.walkingwallofwords.com/)

During the event, Magnum sang 13 songs most of them from In the Aeroplane Over the Sea



Other than the songs from In the Aeroplane Over the Sea, Magnum sang two covers including “Mother” by John Lennon and “I Love How You Love Me” by Phil Spector.

There are existing recordings of the live performance, but there has never been an official release.

I Love How You Love Me paints a picture of a man describing the different attributes of a woman and why he loves her. An overall theme involves the idea that he knows that she loves him (I Love How You Love Me).

The song itself is part of a makeshift unofficial album title, When It All Caved In.

songs.full_title: Oh Comely by Neutral Milk Hotel
songs.title: Oh Comely

description.plain:
A very sexualized song tells the story of someone’s adulterous father. In the story, Mangum juxtaposes vulgarity with the presupposed idea of feminine beauty and purity in an attempt to make sense of the father’s infidelity with what at least the young person perceives to be a prostitute or something similar.

By the end, the overarching theme of Anne Frank comes back into play- where Mangum evokes the idea of the purity of Anne Frank (Mangum has often talked about how she would have been his perfect woman).

In this way, Mangum presents an image of sexuality ruined for someone young who has a traumatized view of women due to his father’s unfaithfulness. The application of Anne Frank’s motif was by Mangum to question his previous suppositions. By packaging and reducing her being to a symbol, he robs both Anne Frank of human agency, and ultimately, the women his father slept with.

Mangum recorded his part of the song—the acoustic guitar and vocals—in one take.

description.plain:
I believe the last two verses are actually another song, untitled as far as I know, yet in most live recordings I’ve heard, they are played as one. This song is simply one A chord, then at the “swimming in your speakers” part, its an A alternating with an E chord. Dark lyrics over simple instrumentation and very emotional delivery.

In a 1996 bootleg from Denver, Jeff says “it’s a song about somebody taking a little …little girl and putting her around a mailbox and making the postmaster a happy person, because he’s on lots of psychedelics.  And We don’t necessarily see that as a very good thing but that’s what this song is about… and it’s also a love song too.”

He also told the interviewer that “Song Against Sex” was written spontaneously, not in several short bursts and pieced together as many Neutral Milk Hotel songs were written.

songs.full_title: The Fool by Neutral Milk Hotel
songs.title: The Fool

description.plain:
This short track, which the end of “Two-Headed Boy” blends into, has the sound of a sinister military march. It may be intended as a transition into the part of the album that deals with subject matter relating to World War II and Anne Frank. The title may imply the foolishness of militarism. The style of the song is also reminiscent of the jazz-laden funeral processions of Jeff Mangum’s hometown of New Orleans, Louisiana.

The Fool is the 0th card in the Major Arcana of the Tarot, which has several subtle references throughout the album (especially on “The King of Carrot Flowers, pt. One”).



“The Fool” also appeared in a short film of the same name, supposedly produced by Elephant 6 associates. Scott Spillane is credited in the final credits of the film. The film appeared at the end of the Elephant 6 documentary.

songs.title: The King of Carrot Flowers, Pts. Two & Three
songs.title_with_featured: The King of Carrot Flowers, Pts. Two & Three

description.plain:
After Pt. One ends with the portrayal of a distorted home (“And mom would drink until she was no longer speaking/And dad would dream of all the different ways to die”) that dissolves into dreamy, spacey drones, Pt. Two continues to build around the drone sound that is accompanied by a distorted banjo playing a balladesque melody while Magnum’s raw voice confesses his love for Jesus Christ.

“The King of Carrot Flowers, Pt. 3” has a rich history as a Neutral Milk Hotel song, appearing on several demo tapes (Hype City Soundtrack and Invent Yourself a Shortcake), usually with different names – “Up and Over”, “Up and Over We Go”, and “Synthetic Flying Machine” have all served time as the name for this song. These don’t seem particularly important, unless one knows the origin of Neutral Milk Hotel – before the Olivia Tremor Control was an early group featuring Jeff and the members of the Tremor Control as “Synthetic Flying Machine.” Despite apparently not having written the lyrics by the time Jittery Joe’s was recorded in March 1997, the lyrics between each version were unchanged.

Robert Schneider, when asked about any happy accidents in the recording process, he

immediately mentioned this song, and the part where Julian’s amplified fuzz-pedaled banjo comes in, right after the drums, in a woozy effect achieved by bowing the strings. “It really bugged me that it was out of tune. But Julian really liked it and Jeff liked it. And Jeff’s not looking for tuning and stuff like that. But now listening to it, I hear that it has a raw, almost Eastern quality of being out of tune.

(from Kim Cooper, “In the Aeroplane over the Sea”)

Jeff has stated that this song about his girlfriend at the time who attempted to kill herself at a holiday party they both attended. Jeff has stated that the girlfriend was and remains the only person he has ever had feelings for.

Almost ten years after this song was written, in 2005, the girl talked about in the song (Jennifer) committed suicide. She apparently struggled as she was a teenage mother at the age of 15, but it is unknown if this led directly to her depression and suicide.

songs.full_title: Two-Headed Boy by Neutral Milk Hotel
songs.title: Two-Headed Boy

description.plain:
“Two-Headed Boy” is an example of Jeff Mangum’s brilliant writing on Neutral Milk Hotel’s sophomore album, In the Aeroplane Over the Sea.

The lyrics most directly alludes to Anne Frank’s isolation while in hiding from the Nazis, though, in the form of allegory, it can also be said to carry across Mangum’s growing feeling of regret after the success of Neutral Milk Hotel. However, Mangum’s writing deliberately allows for many interpretations, such as the “two-headed boy” being a literal boy, a figurative one, or even a cassette tape.

The song is very simple compared to the rest of the album, featuring only Magnum’s powerful vocals and simple acoustic chords. Despite this, it is remembered as one of the best examples of Mangum’s eclectic and cryptic lyrics and unique storytelling.

songs.title: [untitled]

description.plain:
This untitled instrumental, which blends seamlessly into the previous track, “Ghost”, as well as the next track, “Two-Headed Boy, pt. II”, serves as the climax of In the Aeroplane over the Sea as well as the bridge spanning the celebratory “Ghost” and the melancholy “Two-Headed Boy, pt. II”, blending the two moods into the loudest, most distorted moment on the entire disc.

The title of this track is still an area of contention with Neutral Milk Hotel fans because of an alternate title that shows up in various places. “The Penny Arcade in California” appears on Allmusic.com, on the poster included in the Holland, 1945 picture disk (also shown below), and various other music websites. The poster included with “Holland, 1945” also renames “The King of Carrot Flowers, pts. II and III” to “Jesus Christ” and “Up and Over”, respectively, which are titles they were known under before they were included on this album. “Up and Over” specifically appeared on some pre-Avery Island Neutral Milk Hotel releases, under that title as well as “Synthetic Flying Machine”, the name of the band that predated NMH.



This title may be derived from the lead synth in the intro and bridge, which can be compared to the analog sounds produced by arcade machines.

songs.full_title: You've Passed by Neutral Milk Hotel
songs.title: You’ve Passed

description.plain:
“You’ve Passed” was written about Jeff Mangum’s grandmother, who suddenly passed away after Mangum left Seattle. On his way out of Washington, Mangum called his mother who told him his grandmother had died. He has since expressed regret about his inability to attend her funeral.

The song ‘You’ve Passed’ was actually written for my grandmother who passed away right after we left Seattle. I happened to call my Mom while we were in Washington State and she told me that my grandmother had died, and I didn’t even get to go to the funeral. So that song was written for her when I was living in a sort of boiler room connected to a friend’s apartment in Denver.
